The [[English language|English]] [[Derivation (linguistics)|derivational]] [[Prefix (linguistics)|prefix]] '''be-''' is a hold over
from [[Old English language|Old English]]. For the majority of [[native speaker]]s the prefix ''be-'' is no longer
[[productive]]; a possible exception to this is presented by the word ''besmitten'',
which numerous speakers seem to have recreated [http://www.worldwidewords.org/qa/qa-bes2.htm].
Meanings and uses of ''be-'' include: thoroughly, excessively, or more generally,
used as an [[intensifier]]; on, around, over, or generally indicating contact; finally, it is also used to form [[transitive verb]]s from [[noun]]s (e.g. befriend,
behead, benight), [[adjective]]s (e.g. bedim, bewet) or otherwise [[intransitive verb]]s (e.g. bewail, beweep).

